[normal]We
[normal], the Liverpool 
[normal]High Speed
[normal] Too Group,
[normal] believe that the government preferred 
[normal]route 
[normal]for Phase 2 of HS2 is 
[normal]entirely 
[normal]inadequate in term of its provision for 
[normal]the City of 
[normal]Liverpool and the Liverpool City Region. The current proposals, far from ensuring the future prosperity of the city and region, 
[normal]will be of dubious benefit and possibly damaging to its economic prospects.
[normal]The proposals fail Liverpool in the following ways:
[normal]We believe
[normal], and can demonstrate, 
[normal]that the City of Liverpool and the Liverpool City Region are of suffic
[normal]ient size and economic
[normal] importance to justify significant
[normal] infrastructure investment and, therefore, st
[normal]rongly disagree with the 
[normal]current proposal
[normal]s
[normal].
[normal]We recommend that the government demands that HS2 provides a service to Liverpool that helps achieve the stated aim of rebalancing the national economy. Specifically, we recommend that:
[normal]The Liverpool H
[normal]igh 
[normal]S
[normal]peed
[normal] Too Group was formed in response to the publication of the Government Preferred Route for Phase 2 of HS2 in January of this year. We are an independent group of Liverpudlian professionals, broadly supportive of the HS2 scheme but dedicated to the aim of e
[normal]xposing the deficiencies of the current proposals with respect to the proposed Liverpool service.
[normal]1.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Liverpool and 
[normal]its City Region
[normal] represent one of the most important metropolitan regions of the country. 
[normal]Following
[normal] a long period of economic decline
[normal], t
[normal]he last decade has 
[normal]witnessed
[normal] a revival in Liverpool’s fortunes with the successful bid for European Capital of Culture in 2008 and economic developments such as the Liverpool One retail centre, the Arena and Convention 
[normal]Centre an
[normal]d the Cruise Liner Terminal
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This revival does not show any sign of abating. 
[normal]P
[normal]opulation 
[normal]is increasing
[normal] and n
[normal]ext year (2014), Liverpool will host the International Festival of Business showcasing the cit
[normal]y to the world and will 
[normal]see work commence
[normal] on 
[normal]the Liverpool Exhibition Centre at Kings Dock. Infrastructure developments are also taking place – most notably the Liverpool 
[normal]2
[normal] Post-Panamax container port in Sefton and the Mersey Gateway Bridge in Halton. Plans have now been approved for the massive 
[normal]Live
[normal]rpool and Wirral Waters office, commercial and residential developmen
[normal]ts.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]C
[normal]ity 
[normal]R
[normal]egion is host to internationally important 
[normal]industrie
[normal]s including the Jaguar Land Rover factory in Knowsley, the Vauxhall factory and petro-chemical industry in Halton and th
[normal]e pharmaceutical and biotech industries in Liverpool.
[normal] The 
[normal]C
[normal]ity of Liverpool has a large and well-established financial services industry.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]C
[normal]ity has three universities, Liverpool, Liverpool John Moores and Liverpool Hope
[normal] and is an internationally renown
[normal]ed centre for education.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]C
[normal]ity and 
[normal]R
[normal]egion has developed a major tourist industry and possesses some world class tourist attractions including the Albert Dock, Cavern Quarter, Mersey Ferries, Museum 
[normal]Quarter, the Grand National and the two Premier League
[normal] football teams. The 
[normal]C
[normal]ity is an international brand, frequently cited as the most well-known English city outside of London.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Liverpool John Lennon Airport has, in the past fifteen years
[normal],
[normal] developed into a major international airport listed amongst the top 
[normal]ten in the UK and is pursuing further expansion. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Liverpool has 
[normal]a 
[normal]growing c
[normal]ruise liner terminal, which, 
[normal]is 
[normal]de
[normal]veloping as an
[normal] important alternative to the
[normal] e
[normal]stablished south coast ports.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Table 1 (below) shows that Liverpool is the third busiest flow, into 
[normal]and out of London, on the West Coast Main Line. Although Liverpool currently has almost half the annual passenger numbers to London of
[normal] 
[normal]Manchester, it only has a third of the service.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The above demonstrates that Liverpool has a diverse and modern economy f
[normal]or which good connectivity to the national transport network is vital. The current HS2 proposals do not recognise this fact and appear rooted in an outdated image of the city and its economy.
