[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The HS2 proposals ignore the recommendation of the 
[normal]Heseltine / Leahy report (Ref 1) – ‘Government should commit to ensuring Liverpool’s historic parity with Manchester for travel time to London and thereby avoid harmful competitive disadvantage to Liverpool in attracting inward investors.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]report
[normal] 
[normal]accom
[normal]panying the HS2 Phase 2 
[normal]submission 
[normal](Ref 2
[normal]) gives
[normal] minimal attention to the pro
[normal]vision of a Liverpool service.
[normal] Reference is made to a ‘high level’ gauge clearance study and to unspecified routes via Warrington. The conclusion is drawn that the provision of se
[normal]rvices to 
[normal]intermediate destinations
[normal] is more important than an improved Liverpool service.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he attention given to Liverpool falls far 
[normal]short of
[normal] that given to other cities such as Sheffield and Derby, where captive station sites 
[normal]and routes 
[normal]have been
[normal] identified
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] T
[normal]he effect of the Merseyrail network – the most intensive suburban railway network outside of London – in concentrating the Liverpool market is not recognised. The MVA consultancy report
[normal] (Ref.3
[normal])
[normal], on which the HS2 proposals is based, 
[normal]claims t
[normal]hat the Liverpool market is
[normal] ‘polycentric’ 
[normal]based on the odd inclusion of
[normal] 
[normal]Stafford, a station remote from the Liverpool City Region as well as Crewe
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The faster of the two hourly Liverpool services will run for 
[normal]40
[normal] miles on existing tracks.
[normal] The train units o
[normal]n this route section will be restricted to 110mph (175kph), which is slower than the present
[normal] Virgin Pendolinos
[normal]. The journey time over this section is further restricted by two stops
[normal]:
[normal] Runcorn 
[normal]and
[normal] Crewe.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The slower service will run for 75 miles on existing 
[normal]tracks due to a stop at Stafford. It will join HS2 at Lichfield, 
[normal]uniquely 
[normal]making no use 
[normal]of 
[normal]Phase 2 infrastructure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Nine miles of the classic Liverpool route (Chorlton, south of Crewe to Minshull Vernon near Winsford) will run parallel to the HS2 route. Tr
[normal]ains on this section will run at half the speed of the adjacent HS2 captive services (175kph vs 360kph).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The effect of the current proposals on the economy of Liverpool has been evaluated on behalf of HS2 by KPMG, a world leading firm of 
[normal]auditors and acco
[normal]untants
[normal] (Ref.
[normal] 4 and 5
[normal]) 
[normal]. They have calculated two possible outcomes based on assumptions business sensitivity to transport connectivity. The 
[normal]low 
[normal]assumption results in a net gain to the city of 
[normal]£114.95million per annum whereas the high
[normal] assumption results in a net loss of £50.19million. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.9
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The corresponding figures for Preston, which though further from London and smaller than Liverpool
[normal],
[normal] are gains of £178.77million and £141.46million respectively
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.10
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The need for the proposed classic compat
[normal]ible units to share tracks used by relatively slow commuter passenger trains and freight services reduces capacity. This is particularly acute on the double track section of the West Coast Main Line from Crewe to Weaver Junction
[normal] used by services from and t
[normal]o the Port of Liverpool
[normal].
[normal] The freeing up of 
[normal]freight capacity on existing lines is highlighted as a major benefit of HS2, however, in the case of Liverpool, this 
[normal]is 
[normal]clearly not the case
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.11
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Liverpool does not have a Birmingham service provided by HS2 despite h
[normal]aving significantly more passengers to that city than either Leeds or Sheffield
[normal], which
[normal] both enjoy a good connection under current proposals.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Revising the proposed service pattern 
[normal]can significantly improve Liverpool’s current HS2 proposal with minimal investment in infrastructure. Reducing the number of station stops and maximising the use of HS2 high speed infrastructure will allow
[normal] more competitive journey times
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The present propo
[normal]sed route layout has led to Crewe and Stafford being included in the Liverpool service.
[normal] 
[normal]The provision of a
[normal] north junction at Crewe would allow 
[normal]for services from 
[normal]Glasgow and/or Edinburgh 
[normal]to stop at the town, thereby retaining top flight Scottish services an
[normal]d removing an unnecessary Liverpool connection.
[normal] (Crewe to Liverpool w
[normal]ould
[normal] continue t
[normal]o be served by local services).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The removal of the Stafford stop would result in a considerable reduction in journey time for the slower Liverpool service due to the 
[normal]elimi
[normal]nation of both the
[normal] station stop and the 35miles of additional reduced speed running.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Stafford’s rail connection to London could be maintained by a similar solution to that proposed for 
[normal]the 
[normal]nearby and larger city of Stoke on Trent.
[normal]3.2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The following proposals 
[normal]list ways of enhancing the present classic compatible service without developing a full captive service.
[normal] They are not fully developed but illustrate options that do not appear to have been considered by HS2.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Minshu
[normal]ll Vernon Junction: A new junction north of Crewe at the point where the HS2 and West Coast Main Line (WCML) routes diverge allowing Liverpool services to use the HS2 route to by-pass the town. This would remove the parallel running situation outlined in 2
[normal].6 (above).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Cheshire Link Line
[normal]: A new line, some 15km long, linking the HS2 spine route at a point north east of Northwich to Weaver Junction where the Liverpool line branches from the WCML. This would not only allow for a greater length of running at ful
[normal]l linespeed (360kph) and maximum branch linespeed (230kph) but would address the freight capacity issue outlined in 
[normal]2.10 (above). The new line would also improve services to Warrington and could form part of a future captive branch.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]By serving Warrington 
[normal]from the Liverpool route, the opportunity would arise for freeing up a valuable hourly train path on the HS2 spine route. Possible routes are listed below.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]Ditton Freight Route
[normal] – Opening to passenger services of an existing freight line from Ditton
[normal] Junction near Widnes to HS2 south east of Warrington. This would involve reopening the disused Warrington Bank Quay low level station and so providing Warrington with a much improved service. Some realignment of existing tracks and reopening of a section 
[normal]of disused route would be necessary.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Warrington Central Route
[normal]. The connection of HS2 to the existing passenger route from Liverpool to Manchester via Warrington Central via a new curve at Birchwood would be relatively inexpensive and make use of freed up 
[normal]capacity following the completion of the more northerly Chat Moss route. This would reduce the length of classic track running into Liverpool Lime Street to 40km (25 miles).
[normal]3.3.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]To gain the maximum benefit from HS2 investment, a ca
[normal]ptive route taking trains into the city centre is a high priority. Such a line would allow much reduced journey times and far greater capacity. It is the obvious solution for a major city region. The following paragraphs contain suggestions 
[normal]for constructin
[normal]g such a route using a mixture of new and existing infrastructure.
[normal]Figure [bold]1[bold]: Liverpool Captive Route Option[bold]3.3.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Figure 1 illustrates some options for constructing a captive train service into central Liverpool. The numbers in the fol
[normal]lowing paragraphs relate to this figure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Item 1. Liverpool Exchange Station Site – This, largely undeveloped site would have obvious advantages as a Liverpool HS2 terminal due to its proximity to the existing underground Moorfields Station with its Wirral
[normal] and Northern Line services plus its location in the business district of the city and its closeness to the waterfront and cruise liner terminal. It also has very good road access 
[normal]and is
[normal] walking distance of the proposed Liverpool Waters development.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Item 
[normal]2: New approach tunnels from Exchange. Two single track tunnels are likely to be required, although initially, a single 
[normal]track tunnel might suffice
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Item 3: Liverpool Lime Street Station. As Liverpool’s current main line terminus, the development of an HS2
[normal] station here is an alternative to Item 1. The length of station required would 
[normal]mean
[normal] some demolition and / or projection west the current site 
[normal]but could prove a catalyst for the regeneration of the Lime Street area
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]A Northern Line connection to Liverpool 
[normal]Central is possible
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Item 4: The Victoria Tunnel. An existing disused tunnel formerly used for traffic to Liverpool docks. This has sufficient size and straightness to accommodate one line of HS2 track. A new parallel tunnel would take the second track, 
[normal]if required. The tunnel emerges at Edge Hill Station.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Item 5: Edge Hill to Wavertree. A section of disused land north of the current railway would allow two tracks of HS2 to be constructed as far as Wavertree Technology Park Station.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Item 6: The Olive Mo
[normal]unt Cutting. The historic cutting was originally built for four tracks but is now used by two. The unused south side of the cutting could accommodate one track of HS2. The second track would run in tunnel to the north. The route would continue in tunnel to
[normal] Bowring Park where it reaches open land.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.9
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Item 7: The Liverpool Loop Railway. The disused but intact Liverpool Loop Line could form an alternative route for HS2 southwards. I
[normal]t was built for four tracks and so would easily accommodate the two track of HS2. A route to open country is available at Gateacre.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.10
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In total, the 
[normal]length of tunnelling required, in the worst case, would be 7km.
[normal] (This compares favourably with the 1
[normal]2
[normal]km of 
[normal]do
[normal]uble track tunnel required for the branch into Manchester).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.11
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]From the outskirts of Liverpool to HS2, the route would be across country. The nearest point for a connection to HS2 is at Culcheth, north east of Warrington
[normal], some 30km from Liverpool
[normal] (see Figure
[normal] 2 below)
[normal]. 
[normal]The route would be entirely across open country and would follow the M62 motorway to reduce environmental intrusion.
[normal] A parkway station could be provided both to serve Warrington and road traffic from the M62 and M6, so providing a major HS2 faci
[normal]lity for the southern part of the north west region.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.12
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Culcheth route would allow a journey time of around 71 minutes, so competitive with the fastest Manchester journey time of 68 minutes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure [bold]2[bold]: The [bold]Culcheth[bold] Route[bold]3.3.13
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As an 
[normal]alternative, a route from the HS2 spine via Daresbury south west of Warrington would allow for a new parkway station with road and rail access to Runcorn and Warrington. This would require a greater length of track and a Mersey crossing . The route has the
[normal] advantage that it could be developed from the Cheshire Link Route described in paragraph 3.2.3 above.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We believe that HS2 Limited has ignored the potential benefits for the entire network of improving the service for the Liverpool City Regio
[normal]n. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Network Rail in their High Speed Rail proposals of 2009 
[normal](Ref 
[normal]6
[normal])
[normal] 
[normal]estimated that a Liverpool and Warrington Spur would contribute around 5 million London passengers per year.
[normal] A Liverpool Spur would provide journey time savings for around 32mins per journey
[normal] for each of those passengers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Additionally, it would allow 
[normal]the 
[normal]cheap
[normal]er Captive trains to be used
[normal] and
[normal],
[normal] due to improved journey times
[normal],
[normal] only two thirds of the train sets would
[normal] be needed to provide the same service, ringing substantial savings.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A spur would also make additional services viable, adding more benefits and using existing infrastructure more efficiently.  A twice hourly service Liverpool – Warrington – Birmingham wo
[normal]uld 
[normal]increase
[normal] revenues, release capacity for reuse and provide agglomeration benefits for all cities involved.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A spur joining the HS2 spine near Culcheth would create the opportunity of a Liverpool – Warrington – Manchester Airport – Manchester Piccadilly 
[normal]regional “javelin” service
[normal] to improve the current congested and slow service
[normal].  The potential for agglomeration and capacity release are substantial for 
[normal]both cities
[normal] and feed into plans for Manchester’s “Airport City” and 
[normal]the 
[normal]Liverpool Wate
[normal]rs development.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I
[normal]nitial research by Liverpool High Speed Too have show that Liverpool HS2 Spur could have a Benefit Cost Ratio in the “Very High” range (greater than 4.0), excluding any wider eco
[normal]nomic benefits.
